class MyCalendarTwo:
    def __init__(self):
        self.singles = []
        self.doubles = []

    def book(self, start: int, end: int) -> bool:
        for d_start, d_end in self.doubles:
            if start < d_end and end > d_start:
                return False
        for s_start, s_end in self.singles:
            if start < s_end and end > s_start:
                self.doubles.append((max(start, s_start), min(end, s_end)))
        self.singles.append((start, end))
        return True
```


    The algorithm maintains two lists, one for single bookings and one for double bookings. When a new event is added, it first checks if the new event overlaps with any of the double events; if so, it returns false since it would cause a triple booking. Then, it checks if the new event overlaps with any single events, and if so, calculates the overlap and adds it to the list of double events. Finally, adds the new event to the list of single events and returns true. This way, we have an efficient way of avoiding triple bookings using simple iterations and checking.

